            Most Zapier stacks fail for boring reasons.
          </h2>
          <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-zinc-600 leading-relaxed">
            Not because the automation is “hard.”<br/>
            Because ownership is unclear, dependencies are undocumented, and fixes happen after the break.
          </p>

          <div class="mt-6 space-y-3 text-zinc-700 font-semibold">
            <div class="flex gap-3">
              <div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-red-50 border border-red-200 flex items-center justify-center text-red-600 font-black">!</div>
              <div>Workflows tied to personal emails / old credentials</div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex gap-3">
              <div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-red-50 border border-red-200 flex items-center justify-center text-red-600 font-black">!</div>
              <div>No one can explain “what this zap does” during an incident</div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex gap-3">
              <div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-red-50 border border-red-200 flex items-center justify-center text-red-600 font-black">!</div>
              <div>Redundant steps burn tasks for no business value</div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex gap-3">
              <div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-red-50 border border-red-200 flex items-center justify-center text-red-600 font-black">!</div>
              <div>Handovers are “here’s a Loom” — and then panic</div>
